Derive the GTK4 frame-clock interval from the monitor refresh rate on X11
when no compositor supplies frame-timing feedback.

GdkFrameClockIdle hardcodes a 60Hz fallback (FRAME_INTERVAL = 16667us) and
only revises it upward from a compositor's _NET_WM_FRAME_DRAWN /
_NET_WM_FRAME_TIMINGS messages. Standalone X11 compositors (picom etc.) and
bare WMs (dwm) do not send those, so GTK4 animation is capped at 60fps on
high-refresh monitors. This adds a non-reffed back-pointer from the idle
clock to its owning GdkSurface and, when there is no compositor timing
(prev_timings->refresh_interval == 0) on an X11 display, uses
gdk_monitor_get_refresh_rate() of the surface's monitor instead of the
constant. Clamped to [30,1000] Hz. Wayland and compositor-fed X11 are
unaffected (they have a nonzero refresh_interval; Wayland is also excluded by
the GDK_IS_X11_DISPLAY guard).

Downstream antibloat patch, not submitted upstream.
RE-VERIFY ON EVERY gui-libs/gtk VERSION BUMP: it touches the private
GdkFrameClockIdlePrivate struct and gdk_frame_clock_paint_idle(), which change
between GTK releases. Authored against and verified (patch -p1 / git apply
--check) on GTK 4.22.4.

